dismissalText.commentary: Elton Chigumbura c Deonarine b Roach 50 (72b 5x4 0x6 59m) SR: 69.44

dismissalComment.html: big wicket at this time of the game! Elton is gone, the man who could hit the quick runs in the end. Goes for the big shot over the covers, the length is right to go for it, but it's that slight extra pace for Roach and he ends up lobbing it to cover-point

dismissalComment.html: he has given him this time! beats him with the offbreak again, and beats Taylor on the flick. The ball looks good to hit the stumps, but seems to have hit him outside off

commentTextItems.html: that's it, West Indies have levelled the series with a straight shot, straight of mid-off, and turns back towards the pavilion

commentPostTextItems.html: So in drought-hit Guayana, West Indies have ended their drought of international wins, registering their first success in international cricket since August last year. Well done both teams for a close match. Thanks for joining us, this is Sidharth Monga, your commentator, saying goodbye.

Chris Gayle "It is a relief. Hopefully this is the first of many to come. I must say Zimbabwe played really well to push us so far. I must commend the boys on coming back from the defeat. The way I got out in the end I was scared a bit, but Narsingh played really well, and he deserves the Man of the Match. If I had seen the team through, I would have put this innings in one of my top three innings. It was a difficult wicket, they bowled really well, and it was real hard work. Mind over matter."

Narsingh Deonarine is the Man of the Match "Someone had to take the responsibility. The skipper earlier took such a big responsibility, so I needed to bat well with him. A big thank you to the fans too."
Prosper Utseya "Maybe 20 runs short. We just didn't have a partnership up front, we kept losing wickets at crucial points. Just not enough runs on the bard."

Finally Gayle manages a small smile on his face, shakes hands with Otis Gibson and Dave Williams. Zimbabwe are disappointed but they put up a show defending a modest total. Gayle had to play so out of his skin that he went 81 balls without a boundary at one stage of his innings. Deonarine and Gayle finally managed to take West Indies home. The Guyana crowd told the story of the chase: you could almost hear the quiet when West Indies more than 30 overs without a boundary. The pressure built up and built up until home boy Deonarine opened up, and the crowd expressed its glee and cheered even singles. The big crowd - there despite the loss two days ago, there despite the drought - deserved a favourable result. Well done Zimbabwe nonetheless. They were superb with their spinners, on a turning pitch.

commentTextItems.html: defends a length ball back to Price
Deonarine doesn't want any glorious finish, he pushes this down to long-on, takes a single
full delivery, hit powerfully, but straight to mid-off

commentPreTextItems.html: Baynham Goredema from Zimbabwe is hoping for a Malinga four in four! Can Price do it? All deep fielders on the on side

commentTextItems.html: Deonarine playes another lovely shot, steps out and chips it straight down the ground, over mid-off, the idea is to clear the infield and not the ground, and he does that well, and despite a Mastinkeyeri dive the ball reaches the rope
slower ball, bunted into the covers, and Sammy backs away a long way and makes sure Deonarine is on strike to face the next over

commentPreTextItems.html: Gayle has finally taken his pads off

commentTextItems.html: drilled down the ground, a fumble by Elton at long-on gives them the second
walks down the track, makes it into a low fulltoss, can't get it past extra cover

commentPreTextItems.html: Mohamed Z Rahaman takes us back to another match where Milton Pydanna played: The whole Pydanna story started today after another gentleman by the name of Pydanna sent us feedback and Rahaman wondered if it was Milton. Here goes: "That match WI vs Pak in whick M. Pydanna, Kalli, Lloyd and Bacchus played...was a humdinger.
Pak scored all of 127/9 in 40 overs and WI were lucky after G. Greenidge scored 3 of the last ball of the match for the win.
127 is not even a good 20/20 score these days."

commentTextItems.html: yorker, well bowled, dot ball
short again, gets on top of this one, keeps it down, and gets Deonarine on strike
oh Sammy boy, he plays an irresponsible pull shot, gets the top edge that falls short of fine leg

commentPreTextItems.html: 15 off the last four, Deonarine the key for West Indies. Mpofu comes back. Gayle has still not taken his pads off, he still has a stoney look on his face. Baynhama Goredema from Zimbabwe has given up already. He writes, "20 Extras so far! Thats where Zim threw away the game! But we have enjoyed it thoroughly"

commentTextItems.html: and that's another extra, wide down the leg side
nicely played, good good shot, charges down the track, makes it into a half-volley, and then plays it straight down the ground, to the right of long-on, and comes back for two

commentTextItems.html: Deonarine looks to tip and run, but Sammy makes a good call of no as Mpofu is very quick at point
into the pads again, and flicked away to deep square leg; Ray has a word with Sammy as he takes the single
into the pads, misses, can;t get leg-bye either
stays low, Sammy gets the bat down in time, this time Ray has an angry look on his face
oh no another wide, down the leg side, this game would have been closer but for the wides

commentPreTextItems.html: Tyrone: "This batsman pollard reminds me so much of the slugger Ricardo Powel, there tends to be much abuzz of thier batting ability but they never seem to show up for the game." Ray Price, the final throw of the dice, comes back to bowl

commentTextItems.html: Sammy stays back to play a fullish delivery, arms go up in the air, Ray walks towards the batsman, smiles and stares, good drama
pitched outside leg, turning towards middle, defended

dismissalText.commentary: Vusi Sibanda run out (Roach) 5 (3b 1x4 0x6 3m) SR: 166.66

dismissalComment.html: silly running and good work by Roach, out goes Sibanda! Masakadza has dropped this one at his feet, and is called through by Sibanda, but Roach is quick, gets a good bounce, and flicks a direct hit before the Sibanda dive can get him in. Poor call for the run so early on

image.caption: Kemar Roach player portrait
image.longCaption: Kemar Roach player portrait, West Indies media day

dismissalText.commentary: Hamilton Masakadza c Miller b Roach 14 (24b 3x4 0x6 28m) SR: 58.33

dismissalComment.html: soft dismissal! gets under a short delivery and upper-cuts, but doesn't put much power into the shot, just helps it along, and it ends up down Nikita Miller's throat at third man. Roach is kicked, does a windmill celebration, and kisses the West Indies badge on his shirt

dismissalText.commentary: Brendan Taylor lbw b Gayle 47 (66b 4x4 1x6 70m) SR: 71.21

dismissalComment.html: he has given him this time! beats him with the offbreak again, and beats Taylor on the flick. The ball looks good to hit the stumps, but seems to have hit him outside off

dismissalText.commentary: Stuart Matsikenyeri c Gayle b Miller 2 (11b 0x4 0x6 8m) SR: 18.18

dismissalComment.html: soft dismissal but the pressure was on for Matsinkeyeri! looks to push a short delivery into the covers, but it doesn't quite come on and he hits it straight to Gayle at short cover. Easy catch

dismissalText.commentary: Chris Mpofu run out (Gayle/†Fletcher) 0 (2b 0x4 0x6 2m) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: Zimbabwe's innings is over! gets a leading edge one bounce to Gayle at cover. He wants a single but is sent back and is late in going back, and is found short

dismissalText.commentary: Chris Gayle b Cremer 88 (111b 7x4 2x6 155m) SR: 79.27

dismissalComment.html: one big shot too many! Cremer has got the big wicket! Gayle charges down the wicket, doesn't get close to the pitch of the ball, ends up swinging outside the line and is bowled, but it's been a superb knock on a testing wicket
